# Experiment 05: Dockerfile build variant (FROM ubuntu:24.04 + COPY) on Daytona
date: 2026-06-14
command: harbor run -p experiment-logs/05-dockerfile-experiment/check-task \
         -m anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6 -a claude-code -e daytona
task: novel wrapper, FROM ubuntu:24.04 + COPY task /task (no docker_image),
      test.sh installs python3 via apt at verify time.

## Result: FAILED (VerifierTimeoutError), total 5m41s
Timeline (from trial mtimes), job 2026-06-14__14-08-22:
  14:08:22 -> 14:11:00  (~2m38s)  image build + sandbox start + agent bootstrap
  14:11:00 -> 14:12:00  (~60s)    agent ran the review (succeeded; wrote result)
  14:12:02 -> 14:14:04  (122s)    verifier ran -> TIMED OUT at 120s limit
verifier/ is empty: test.sh was killed mid-run, before writing reward.

## What it proves
1. The build did NOT stall. Novel ubuntu:24.04 + COPY reached the agent in
   ~2.6 min, NOT the 16 min the python:3.13-slim build took. => the 16 min was
   the python:3.13-slim BASE (cold on Daytona's builder), not novelty.
   => "whole-image global cache" theory is largely refuted; "warm ubuntu base"
   theory holds.
2. A new villain: apt is SLOW on Daytona's ubuntu sandbox. `apt-get install
   python3` alone blew the 120s verifier timeout, and likely padded the agent
   bootstrap (which also apt-installs curl/procps) toward that ~2.6 min.

## Decision: KEEP the prebuilt python:3.13-slim approach (run-04, 92s)
The Dockerfile+ubuntu path is viable on build speed but strictly worse here:
validate.py needs python3, ubuntu lacks it, and installing python3 (at verify
time OR via RUN at build time) means slow Daytona apt. The prebuilt
python:3.13-slim image already has python3 (+ tar/gzip), so it never touches
apt for python, no build, fastest, and it's the only variant that succeeded.
